## **SSL certificate errors on `git push` / `git fetch` (Windows)**

- **Symptom** (seen repeatedly on `mosc-temp` and other HTTPS remotes):
  ```
  fatal: unable to access 'https://github.com/...': SSL certificate problem: unable to get local issuer certificate
  ```
- **Cause:** Git for Windows cannot validate the HTTPS server certificate chain (missing/intermediate CA, corporate SSL inspection, or outdated CA bundle).
- **Temporary workaround (current session only — use only to unblock a push):**
  ```powershell
  cd F:\project_workspace\<repo>
  $env:GIT_SSL_NO_VERIFY = "true"
  git push
  Remove-Item Env:GIT_SSL_NO_VERIFY
  ```
  - **Do not** set `git config http.sslVerify false` globally.
  - **Do not** leave `GIT_SSL_NO_VERIFY` set in your user or system environment.
- **Proper fix (preferred — pick one):**
  1. **Update Git for Windows** — [https://git-scm.com/download/win](https://git-scm.com/download/win)
  2. **Corporate proxy / SSL inspection** — `git config --global http.sslCAInfo "C:/path/to/corporate-ca-bundle.pem"`
  3. **Switch the remote to SSH** — `git remote set-url origin git@github.com:org/repo.git`
- **Verify after fix:** `git ls-remote origin HEAD`

